"# Chapter 17 — Frames Buffered

There is a moment in every kid's first hour with Motoi where they type

```scheme
(circle 10 10 5)
```

into the REPL, hit enter, and nothing happens. Something happened — the pixels landed in the framebuffer. But the REPL prints `()` and the kid stares at it and concludes graphics don't work.

They do work. The missing pieces are two verbs and one habit:

- `(begin-frame)` — start collecting drawing calls for this frame.
- `(end-frame)` — stop collecting.
- `(render)` — hand the finished frame to whatever's showing it.

Wrap your drawing in those three and the pixels *appear*. Every scene in this chapter follows the same skeleton:

```scheme
(clear)         ; wipe the previous frame
(begin-frame)   ; start recording
;; ... draw stuff ...
(end-frame)     ; stop recording
(render)        ; show it
```

If nothing else in this chapter sticks, that skeleton should. The next ten sections are ten scenes built from it — some standing still, some moving, some listening to keys, some making sound. Each one is a complete runnable program. Each one has been verified. If you type it in exactly and don't see the picture, something is wrong with the runtime, not with you.

The scenes deliberately mix two ways of naming the same thing. Motoi has one true drawing verb per shape — `rect`, `rect-fill`, `pset` — and a handful of aliases (`rectangle`, `fill-rect`, `filled-rectangle`, `draw-rect`, `pixel`, `put-pixel`, `set-pixel!`, `plot-pixel`) that dispatch to the same code. Every alias appears somewhere in the ten scenes below. The point is that whichever name your fingers already know from another Scheme, another drawing library, another day, it just works.

The framebuffer is 80 pixels by 80 pixels unless you call `(set-mode w h)` to change it. Coordinates start at `(0, 0)` in the top-left. Y grows downward, which is confusing the first time and normal after.

## 17.1 A house

Every kid's graphics journey starts with a house. Sky on top, grass underneath, a square box for the walls, a triangle for the roof, a door, a window, and a sun off in the corner. Six shapes layered back to front, six colors. If you have ever drawn a house in crayon you already know how to write this.

```scheme
;; A house — the composed scene that starts every kid's graphics journey.
(clear)
(begin-frame)
;; sky
(set-color 'blue)
(rect-fill 0 0 80 55)
;; grass
(set-color 'green)
(rect-fill 0 55 80 25)
;; house body
(set-color 'brown)
(rect-fill 25 40 30 25)
;; roof — a triangle out of three lines
(set-color 'red)
(line 25 40 40 25)
(line 40 25 55 40)
(line 25 40 55 40)
;; door
(set-color 'dark-purple)
(rect-fill 37 50 7 15)
;; window
(set-color 'yellow)
(rect-fill 28 45 6 6)
;; sun
(set-color 'orange)
(disc 68 12 6)
(end-frame)
(render)
```

**What you see.** A blue sky, green grass, a brown box with a red triangular roof, a purple door, a small yellow window, and an orange sun in the top right. Order matters — the sky went first so everything else paints over it. If you drew the sky last, the sky would cover the house.

## 17.2 A moon rising over hills

Night sky, a scatter of stars, a crescent moon made by drawing a smaller dark disc over a lighter one, and three overlapping dark-green discs sitting low on the frame that read as hills. The trick worth stealing: you can subtract shapes by painting the background color over them.

```scheme
;; A moon rising over hills — night scene with a single bright dot for a star.
(clear)
(begin-frame)
;; night sky
(set-color 'dark-blue)
(rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
;; a scatter of stars — single pixels
(set-color 'white)
(pset 8 5)
(pset 15 12)
(pset 22 8)
(pset 33 15)
(pset 48 6)
(pset 62 11)
(pset 74 14)
;; the moon
(set-color 'yellow)
(disc 60 22 8)
;; a bite taken out of the moon so it reads as a crescent
(set-color 'dark-blue)
(disc 55 20 7)
;; distant hills — two overlapping arcs faked with discs low on the frame
(set-color 'dark-green)
(disc 20 78 22)
(disc 55 82 25)
(disc 78 80 18)
;; the horizon line
(set-color 'green)
(line 0 60 79 60)
(end-frame)
(render)
```

**What you see.** A dark blue sky, seven white star pixels, a yellow crescent moon (the missing bite is the color of the sky), a green horizon line, and three overlapping dark-green hills poking up from the bottom. Compose it, then take one shape away — the scene falls apart. Every element is doing work.

## 17.3 A flag on a pole

Three colored stripes, an outline around them, a pole underneath, and a knob on top. This is the first scene to use one of the alias names — `rectangle` instead of `rect`. If your fingers learned `rectangle` in another language, use it here; the framebuffer doesn't care which name you typed.

```scheme
;; A flag on a pole.
;; Uses the `rectangle` alias (a synonym for `rect`) — canonical in
;; most other Scheme graphics libs, and typing it should just work.
(clear)
(begin-frame)
;; sky
(set-color 'blue)
(rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
;; the pole
(set-color 'dark-grey)
(line 20 15 20 70)
;; the flag — three horizontal stripes
(set-color 'red)
(rect-fill 20 15 40 8)
(set-color 'white)
(rect-fill 20 23 40 8)
(set-color 'green)
(rect-fill 20 31 40 8)
;; an outline around the whole flag using the `rectangle` alias
(set-color 'black)
(rectangle 20 15 40 24)
;; the star knob at the top of the pole
(set-color 'yellow)
(disc 20 13 3)
(end-frame)
(render)
```

**What you see.** A pale blue sky, a grey vertical pole, a horizontal tricolor flag (red-white-green) with a black border, and a small yellow knob at the pole's top.

## 17.4 A face

Two eyes, two pupils, a nose, a mouth. The face is a filled peach disc with a brown outline. The pupils are single pixels, drawn using the `pixel` alias. One tiny dot in the middle of the eye is the difference between the face looking at you and the face staring past you.

```scheme
;; A face — head, eyes, mouth. Two lines and some circles.
;; Uses the `pixel` alias for single-dot pupils.
(clear)
(begin-frame)
;; background
(set-color 'lavender)
(rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
;; head — a big filled disc
(set-color 'peach)
(disc 40 40 25)
;; outline the head
(set-color 'brown)
(circle 40 40 25)
;; eyes — the whites
(set-color 'white)
(disc 30 34 4)
(disc 50 34 4)
;; pupils — single pixels using the `pixel` alias
(set-color 'black)
(pixel 30 34)
(pixel 50 34)
;; mouth — a smile drawn as two short lines
(set-color 'red)
(line 30 50 40 55)
(line 40 55 50 50)
;; a nose — a tiny line down the middle
(set-color 'brown)
(line 40 40 40 46)
(end-frame)
(render)
```

**What you see.** A round peach face on a lavender background. Two small white eyes with black pupils centered inside them. A short brown nose. A red smile made of two lines meeting at the chin.

## 17.5 A bouncing ball

The first animation. `on-frame` installs a callback that runs every frame; `tick-frame` advances the loop one step deterministically (useful in scripts — in the REPL the loop runs on its own). The ball accelerates down, hits the floor, loses some energy, and bounces.

```scheme
;; A bouncing ball — the first animation.
;; on-frame installs a callback; tick-frame advances the loop
;; deterministically for scripts (in a REPL the loop runs on its own).
(define ball-y 10)
(define ball-vy 1)

(on-frame
  (lambda (f)
    ;; physics — accelerate down, bounce off the floor
    (set! ball-vy (+ ball-vy 1))
    (set! ball-y (+ ball-y ball-vy))
    (if (>= ball-y 70)
        (begin
          (set! ball-y 70)
          (set! ball-vy (- 0 (quotient (* ball-vy 3) 4)))))
    ;; draw
    (clear)
    (begin-frame)
    (set-color 'blue)
    (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
    (set-color 'green)
    (rect-fill 0 72 80 8)
    (set-color 'red)
    (disc 40 ball-y 5)
    (end-frame)))

;; tick 20 frames — enough for one full arc + a bounce
(let loop ((i 0))
  (if (< i 20)
      (begin (tick-frame) (loop (+ i 1)))))
(render)
```

**What you see (motion).** A red disc falls from near the top of a blue sky onto a green floor at the bottom, bounces once at reduced height, and rests. In the REPL, `(on-frame ...)` alone kicks off the loop and you watch the animation live; in the script version, `tick-frame` is what advances time.

## 17.6 Rain

Twenty little drops per frame, each a short vertical line with a single-pixel head. The drops are placed pseudo-randomly using a tiny linear congruential generator so the demo is deterministic. This one uses the `put-pixel` alias for the drop heads.

```scheme
;; Rain — pseudo-random drops that streak down and repeat.
;; Uses the `put-pixel` alias for the drop heads.
;; A tiny LCG stands in for randomness so the demo is deterministic.
(define seed 1)
(define (next-rand)
  (set! seed (remainder (+ (* seed 1103515245) 12345) 2147483648))
  seed)
(define (rand-mod n) (remainder (next-rand) n))

(on-frame
  (lambda (f)
    (clear)
    (begin-frame)
    ;; storm-grey sky
    (set-color 'dark-grey)
    (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
    ;; puddled ground
    (set-color 'dark-blue)
    (rect-fill 0 72 80 8)
    ;; twenty drops per frame, streaked
    (set-color 'blue)
    (let loop ((i 0))
      (if (< i 20)
          (let ((x (rand-mod 80))
                (y (rand-mod 72)))
            (line x y x (+ y 3))     ; streak
            (put-pixel x (+ y 3))    ; the drop head
            (loop (+ i 1)))))
    (end-frame)))

(tick-frame)
(tick-frame)
(tick-frame)
(render)
```

**What you see (motion).** A dark grey scene with a strip of dark blue puddle across the bottom. Twenty pale blue vertical streaks per frame, each ending in a single-pixel drop head. Every frame regenerates. In the REPL it looks like real rain; in scripts you get one frozen snapshot per `tick-frame`.

## 17.7 A tone drawn as its own shape

Sound and picture on the same timeline. A C major scale plays, and as each note fires, a yellow bar grows taller. The bar height encodes pitch: low note, short bar; high note, tall bar. You hear the scale climb, and you see it climb.

```scheme
;; A tone drawn as its own shape.
;; When you hear the note, the frame shows the frequency as a bar.
;; A scale plays and the bar grows with the pitch.
(define (note->freq semitones)
  (* 440 (expt 2 (/ semitones 12.0))))

(define scale (list -9 -7 -5 -4 -2 0 2 3))   ; C major, C4→C5

(define (draw-bar height)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'black)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
  (set-color 'yellow)
  ;; a vertical bar centered — taller for higher notes
  (rect-fill 30 (- 70 height) 20 height)
  (set-color 'white)
  (rectangle 30 (- 70 height) 20 height)
  (end-frame))

(for-each
  (lambda (semi)
    (tone (note->freq semi) 0.15)
    (draw-bar (+ 10 (* 5 (+ semi 9)))))
  scale)

(render)
```

**What you see and hear.** Eight sine-wave notes rising from middle C to C5, at 150 ms each. For each note, a yellow bar with a white outline paints on a black frame. The bar grows taller with each higher note. The final rendered frame shows the last (tallest) bar.

## 17.8 Catch the pixel

The first game. A paddle at the bottom of the screen catches a falling pixel. Left and right arrow keys move the paddle. Every time the paddle catches the pixel, a white dot lights up along the top of the screen — the score. This one uses two aliases: `filled-rectangle` for the paddle and `set-pixel!` for the falling drop.

```scheme
;; Catch the pixel — a small game shape.
;; A paddle at the bottom follows the arrow keys; a single pixel
;; falls from the top. Score a point when the paddle catches it.
;; Uses `filled-rectangle` for the paddle and `set-pixel!` for the drop.
(define paddle-x 35)
(define drop-x 20)
(define drop-y 0)
(define score 0)

(on-key
  (lambda (k)
    (cond
      ((eq? k 'left)  (set! paddle-x (max 0 (- paddle-x 4))))
      ((eq? k 'right) (set! paddle-x (min 70 (+ paddle-x 4)))))))

(on-frame
  (lambda (f)
    ;; drop physics
    (set! drop-y (+ drop-y 2))
    (if (> drop-y 78)
        (begin
          ;; caught if the pixel lands over the paddle
          (if (and (>= drop-x paddle-x) (<= drop-x (+ paddle-x 10)))
              (set! score (+ score 1)))
          (set! drop-y 0)
          (set! drop-x (remainder (+ (* drop-x 7) 13) 78))))
    (clear)
    (begin-frame)
    ;; background + score line
    (set-color 'dark-blue)
    (rect-fill 0 0 80 80)
    ;; the paddle
    (set-color 'peach)
    (filled-rectangle paddle-x 74 10 3)
    ;; the drop
    (set-color 'yellow)
    (set-pixel! drop-x drop-y)
    ;; score marks — one white pixel per point along the top row
    (set-color 'white)
    (let loop ((i 0))
      (if (< i score)
          (begin (pset (+ 2 (* i 2)) 2) (loop (+ i 1)))))
    (end-frame)))

;; Simulate one press and 60 frames.
(fire-key 'right)
(fire-key 'right)
(let loop ((i 0))
  (if (< i 60)
      (begin (tick-frame) (loop (+ i 1)))))
(render)
```

**What you see (interactive).** A dark blue field. A small peach paddle sits near the bottom, movable with the left and right arrow keys. A single yellow pixel falls from the top. When it hits the bottom, one of two things happens: the paddle was under it (a white score-pixel appears at the top) or the paddle wasn't (nothing lights up). Either way the pixel resets to the top and falls again. `fire-key` in the script version is how you simulate keypresses without a keyboard.

## 17.9 A sunrise

The sun climbs, the sky shifts through moods, and each frame plays a rising note as the sun rises. A soft closing note fires at the end. This is the first scene to fold together animation, changing color state, and pitch that tracks position.

```scheme
;; Sunrise — the sun climbs and the sky brightens.
;; Each dawn frame plays a rising note. The last frame plays a soft chord.
(define sun-y 80)

(define (sky-color y)
  ;; further from the horizon → darker blue
  (cond
    ((> y 60) 'dark-blue)
    ((> y 40) 'blue)
    ((> y 20) 'lavender)
    (else     'peach)))

(on-frame
  (lambda (f)
    (set! sun-y (max 15 (- sun-y 3)))
    (clear)
    (begin-frame)
    ;; sky in the current mood
    (set-color (sky-color sun-y))
    (rect-fill 0 0 80 60)
    ;; ground
    (set-color 'brown)
    (rect-fill 0 60 80 20)
    ;; hills
    (set-color 'dark-green)
    (disc 25 62 12)
    (disc 60 65 15)
    ;; sun
    (set-color 'yellow)
    (disc 40 sun-y 8)
    (set-color 'orange)
    (circle 40 sun-y 8)
    (end-frame)
    ;; a rising note as the sun climbs
    (tone (+ 220 (* 4 (- 80 sun-y))) 0.05)))

;; 20 ticks — the sun rises from 80 to ~20
(let loop ((i 0))
  (if (< i 20)
      (begin (tick-frame) (loop (+ i 1)))))

;; a soft closing note
(note 'C5 0.3)
(render)
```

**What you see and hear.** A yellow sun climbs from below the horizon toward the top of the frame. As it rises, the sky shifts from dark blue to blue to lavender to peach. Two dark-green hills sit on brown ground. A short sine-wave tone plays every frame, rising in pitch as the sun rises. At the end, a single C5 note plays as a closing beat.

## 17.10 A small demo

The final scene folds everything in: a starfield, a color marquee, a bouncing shape, and two-note beats fired on a schedule tied to the frame counter. The last three aliases — `draw-rect`, `fill-rect`, `plot-pixel` — all appear here.

```scheme
;; A small demo scene — everything at once.
;; Marquee text simulated as a colored bar, a bouncing shape, star field,
;; and a two-note motif that fires with the beat. This uses the last
;; three aliases: `draw-rect`, `fill-rect`, and `plot-pixel`.

(define seed 7)
(define (next-rand)
  (set! seed (remainder (+ (* seed 1103515245) 12345) 2147483648))
  seed)
(define (rand-mod n) (remainder (next-rand) n))

(define shape-x 40)
(define shape-vx 3)

(on-frame
  (lambda (f)
    ;; bounce the shape
    (set! shape-x (+ shape-x shape-vx))
    (if (or (< shape-x 8) (> shape-x 72))
        (set! shape-vx (- 0 shape-vx)))
    (clear)
    (begin-frame)
    ;; black space background
    (set-color 'black)
    (fill-rect 0 0 80 80)
    ;; star field — random single pixels using plot-pixel
    (set-color 'white)
    (let loop ((i 0))
      (if (< i 15)
          (begin
            (plot-pixel (rand-mod 80) (rand-mod 80))
            (loop (+ i 1)))))
    ;; a horizon bar
    (set-color 'dark-purple)
    (fill-rect 0 55 80 4)
    ;; the \"marquee\" — colored bar at the top
    (set-color 'pink)
    (fill-rect 5 5 70 8)
    ;; frame it with draw-rect
    (set-color 'white)
    (draw-rect 5 5 70 8)
    ;; the bouncing shape
    (set-color 'yellow)
    (disc shape-x 40 6)
    (set-color 'orange)
    (circle shape-x 40 6)
    (end-frame)
    ;; every 4th frame plays a beat
    (if (= (remainder f 4) 0) (tone 220 0.05))
    (if (= (remainder f 8) 0) (tone 440 0.05))))

(let loop ((i 0))
  (if (< i 16)
      (begin (tick-frame) (loop (+ i 1)))))
(render)
```

**What you see and hear.** A black field with fifteen white star pixels. A pink marquee bar with a white outline near the top. A dark-purple horizon line across the middle. A yellow-and-orange disc bouncing left and right through the center. A low tone every fourth frame, a higher tone every eighth frame — a simple two-note motif. Sixteen frames total in the script version; the REPL version keeps running.

## 17.11 Now build your own

You have ten skeletons. Each one starts with `(clear)`, wraps drawing in `(begin-frame)` and `(end-frame)`, and ends with `(render)`. Animation just puts the drawing inside `(on-frame ...)`; input adds `(on-key ...)`; sound adds `(tone ...)` or `(note ...)`. The verbs compose. Try:

- Change the house's colors. Add a chimney.
- Give the moon two crescent shapes. Add a shooting star that moves per frame.
- Turn the flag into your country's flag (or make one up).
- Give the face eyebrows. Make it wink by leaving one eye closed on odd frames.
- Add gravity to catch-the-pixel. Add a lose condition.
- Layer three scales in the tone-shape scene, one after another.

If you type `(circle 10 10 5)` and nothing happens, remember: you forgot the frame. Wrap it. Render. There it is.
")
